Definition \thedefn. The suspension $\Sigma(X)$ of a space $X$ is the pushout of the diagram $\mathbf{1}\leftarrow X\rightarrow\mathbf{1}$. More concretely, the suspension of $X$ has basic constructors $\displaystyle\mathsf{N}$ $\displaystyle:\Sigma(X)$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{S}$ $\displaystyle:\Sigma(X)$ $\displaystyle\mathsf{merid}$ $\displaystyle:X\to(\mathsf{N}=\mathsf{S}).$
Definition \thedefn. Let $f:X\to Y$ is a morphism in a locally cartesian closed category $\mathcal{A}$. The polynomial functor $P_{f}$ associated to $f$ is the endofunctor $\tikzcd\mathcal{A}\ar{r}{X\times{-}}&\mathcal{A}/X\ar{r}{\Pi_{f}}&\mathcal{A}/% Y\ar{r}{\Sigma_{f}}&\mathcal{A}$ An initial algebra for $P_{f}$ is called the $\mathsf{W}$-type associated to $f$, or $\mathsf{W}_{f}$. The category $\mathcal{A}$ is said to have $\mathsf{W}$-types if all the polynomial functors have initial algebras.
Definition \thedefn. An equivalence relation over a type $A$ consists of a mere relation $R:A\to A\to\mathsf{Prop}$ which is reflexive, symmetric and transitive, i.e. there are elements $\displaystyle\rho$ $\displaystyle:\mathchoice{{\textstyle\prod_{(x:A)}}}{\prod_{(x:A)}}{\prod_{(x:% A)}}{\prod_{(x:A)}}R(x,x)$ $\displaystyle\sigma$ $\displaystyle:\mathchoice{{\textstyle\prod_{(x,y:A)}}}{\prod_{(x,y:A)}}{\prod_% {(x,y:A)}}{\prod_{(x,y:A)}}R(x,y)\to R(y,x)$ $\displaystyle\tau$ $\displaystyle:\mathchoice{{\textstyle\prod_{(x,y,z:A)}}}{\prod_{(x,y,z:A)}}{% \prod_{(x,y,z:A)}}{\prod_{(x,y,z:A)}}R(y,z)\to R(x,y)\to R(x,z).$ We also write $\mathsf{isEqRel}(R)$ for the type witnessing that $R$ is an equivalence relation.
Definition \thedefn. A morphism $f:A\to B$ is said to be a cover if the only monomorphism (up to isomorphism) through which $f$ factors is $B=$.
Definition \thedefn. Let $D$ be a diagram of shape $\Gamma$, let $A$ be a type. For any cone $\tau$ with vertex $A$ and for any type $B$, there is a function $\mathsf{coneMap}(\tau,B):(B\to A)\to\mathsf{cone}_{D}(B)$ defined by ${\lambda}f.\,{\mathopen{}(\tau_{0}\circ f,\tau_{1}\circ f)\mathclose{}}$. Here $\tau_{0}\circ f$ is defined by ${\lambda}x.\,{\lambda}b.\,\tau(x,f(b))$ and $\tau_{1}\circ f$ is defined by ${\lambda}x.\,{\lambda}y.\,{\lambda}e.\,{\lambda}b.\,\tau_{1}(e,f(b))$. Likewise, for any cocone $\tau$ with vertex $A$ and for any $B$, there is a function $\mathsf{coconeMap}(\tau,B):(A\to B)\to\mathsf{cocone}_{D}(B)$ defined by ${\lambda}f.\,{\mathopen{}(f\circ\tau_{0},f\circ\tau_{1})\mathclose{}}$. Here, the function $f\circ\tau_{1}$ is stricty speaking not really a composition; it is defined by ${\lambda}x.\,{\lambda}y.\,{\lambda}e.\,{\lambda}d.\,\mathsf{ap}_{f}(\tau_{1}(e% ,d))$.
Definition 1.1.1. A localizing subcategory of a triangulated category ${\mathcal{T}}$ is a full triangulated subcategory $\mathcal{L}\subset{\mathcal{T}}$ stable under arbitrary sums. If $S$ is a set of objects in ${\mathcal{T}}$, then the smallest triangulated category containing $S$ is called the localizing subcategory generated by $S$ and denoted by $\operatorname{Loc}(S)$. Similarly, using products instead of sums we get the notion of a colocalizing subcategory and a colocalizing subcategory generated by $S$, denoted by $\operatorname{Coloc}(S)$.
Definition 1.1.9. A full subcategory $I$ of a tensor triangulated category $({\mathcal{T}},\otimes,\mathbf{1})$, is a thick tensor ideal, if it is (1) a full triangulated subcategory, (2) closed under finite sums, (3) thick: if $a\oplus b\in I$ then $a\in I$ and $b\in I$, (4) absorbing for the tensor product: if $a\in I$ and $b\in{\mathcal{T}}$ then $a\otimes b\in I$.
Definition 7.1. We say that $\mathsf{T}$ is stratified by the action of $R$ if $\varGamma_{\mathfrak{p}}\mathsf{T}$ is minimal for each $\mathfrak{p}\in\operatorname{Spec}R$. In the same vein, $\operatorname{\mathsf{Coh}}\mathsf{T}$ is stratified by the action of $R$ if $\operatorname{\mathsf{Coh}}\varGamma_{\mathfrak{p}}\mathsf{T}$ is minimal for each $\mathfrak{p}\in\operatorname{Spec}R$.
Definition 3.1. [9] The $Q$-topological space $(Q,\nu)$ is called the $Q$-Sierpinski space.
Definition 2.1. Let $\Omega=(n_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in I}$ be a class of cardinal numbers. • An $\Omega$-algebra is a pair $(A,(\omega_{\lambda}^{A})_{\lambda\in I})$ consisting of a set $A$ and a family of maps $\omega_{\lambda}^{A}:A^{n_{\lambda}}\rightarrow A$. $B\subseteq A$ is called a subalgebra of $(A,(\omega_{\lambda}^{A})_{\lambda\in I})$ if $\omega_{\lambda}^{A}((b_{i})_{i\in n_{\lambda}})\in B$, for every $\lambda\in I$ and every $(b_{i})_{i\in n_{\lambda}}\in B^{n_{\lambda}}$. Given $S\subseteq A$, $\langle S\rangle$ denotes the subalgebra of $(A,(\omega_{\lambda}^{A})_{\lambda\in I})$ ‘generated by $S$’, i.e., $\langle S\rangle$ is the intersection of all subalgebras of $(A,(\omega_{\lambda}^{A})_{\lambda\in I})$ containing $S$. (In fact, $\langle S\rangle=\{\omega_{\lambda}^{A}({\langle s_{i}\rangle}_{i\in n_{% \lambda}})$ $|$ $s_{i}\in S$ and $\lambda\in I\}$). • Given $\Omega$-algebras $(A,(\omega_{\lambda}^{A})_{\lambda\in I})$ and $(B,(\omega_{\lambda}^{B})_{\lambda\in I})$, a map $f:A\rightarrow B$ is called an $\Omega$-algebra homomorphism provided that for every $\lambda\in I$, the following diagram $\xymatrix{A^{n_{\lambda}}\ar[d]_{\omega_{\lambda}^{A}}\ar[r]^{f^{n_{\lambda}}}% &B^{n_{\lambda}}\ar[d]^{\omega_{\lambda}^{B}}\\ A\ar[r]_{f}&B}$ commutes. Let ${\bf Alg}(\Omega)$ denote the category of $\Omega$-algebras and $\Omega$-algebra homomorphisms (this category has products). • A variety of $\Omega$-algebras is a full subcategory of ${\bf Alg}(\Omega)$ which is closed under the formation of products, subalgebras, and homomorphic images. Throughout this paper, $\Omega=(n_{\lambda})_{\lambda\in I}$ denotes a fixed class of cardinal numbers, A denotes a fixed variety of $\Omega$-algebras and $Q$ denotes a fixed member of A. Each function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ between sets $X$ and $Y$ gives rise to two functions $f^{\leftarrow}:2^{Y}\rightarrow 2^{X}$ and $f^{\rightarrow}:2^{X}\rightarrow 2^{Y}$, given by $f^{\leftarrow}(B)=\{x\in X$ $|$ $f(x)\in B\}$ and $f^{\rightarrow}(A)=\{f(x)$ $|$ $x\in A\}$, and also a function $f_{Q}^{\leftarrow}:Q^{Y}\rightarrow Q^{X}$, given by $f_{Q}^{\leftarrow}(\alpha)=\alpha\circ f$. • Given a set $X$, a subset $\tau$ of $Q^{X}$ is called a $Q$-topology on $X$ if $\tau$ is a subalgebra of $Q^{X}$, in which case, the pair $(X,\tau)$ is called a $Q$-topological space. • Given two $Q$-topological spaces $(X,\tau)$ and $(Y,\eta)$, a $Q$-continuous function from $(X,\tau)$ to $(Y,\eta)$ is a function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ such that $f_{Q}^{\leftarrow}(\alpha)\in\tau$, for every $\alpha\in\eta$. • Given a $Q$-topological space $(X,\tau)$ and $Y\subseteq X$, $(i_{Q}^{\leftarrow})^{\rightarrow}(\tau)$ $(=\{p\circ i$ $|$ $p\in\tau\})$ is called the ${\bf{\it Q}}$-subspace topology on $Y$, where $i:Y\rightarrow X$ is the inclusion map. We shall denote the $Q$-subspace topology on $Y$ as $\tau_{Y}$. • A $Q$-topological space $(X,\tau)$ is called $Q$-${\bf T_{0}}$ if for every distinct $x,y\in X$, there exists $p\in\tau$ such that $p(x)\neq p(y)$.
Definition 2.2. [1, 2] $\mathscr{R}$ is said to be epireflective in $\mathscr{C}$ if for each $\mathscr{C}$-object $X$, there exists an epimorphism $r_{X}:X\rightarrow RX$, with $RX\in ob\mathscr{R}$, such that for each $\mathscr{C}$-morphism $f:X\rightarrow Y$, with $Y\in ob\mathscr{R}$, there exists a unique $\mathscr{R}$-morphism $f^{*}:RX\rightarrow Y$, such that $f^{*}\circ r_{X}=f$. If moreover, each $r_{X}\in\mathscr{H}$ and $f^{*}$ is a $\mathscr{C}$-isomorphism, whenever $f\in epi\mathscr{C}\bigcap\mathscr{H}$, then $\mathscr{R}$ is said to be an $\mathscr{H}$-firm epireflective subcategory of $\mathscr{C}$ (or that the epireflectivity of $\mathscr{R}$ in $\mathscr{C}$ is $\mathscr{H}$-firm).
Definition 3.2. [9] A $Q$-topological space $(X,\tau)$ is called $Q$-sober if $\eta_{X}$ is bijective.
Definition A.9. Let $X$ be an arbitrary Banach space. A series $\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}a_{i}$ is subseries convergent when the partial sums $A_{n}=\sum_{j=0}^{n}\alpha(j)a_{j}$ form a Cauchy sequence, for arbitrary choice of $\alpha:\mathbb{N}\rightarrow\{0,1\}$. Subseries convergence is often defined informally as ‘each subseries of $\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}a_{i}$ converges’.
Definition 5.1. Given ${\mathcal{D}}\in Ob(\mbox{\bf cCat})$, and ${{\mathcal{C}}}\in Ob(\mbox{\bf Cat}_{\Sigma})$, we define $\sigma_{{\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{D}}}:{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]\rightarrow{{% \mathcal{C}}}$ by • (on objects) $\sigma_{{\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{D}}}(X,U)=X$, for all $(X,U)\in Ob({\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}])$. • (on arrows) Given $h\in{{\mathcal{C}}}[D]((X,U),(Y,V))$, then $\sigma_{{\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{D}}}(h)=\sum_{a\in{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)}h(a)\ \in% \ {{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y).$
Definition A.1. ($\Sigma$-monoids, Partially additive monoids) A PCM $(M,\Sigma)$ is called a $\Sigma$-monoid when it satisfies the following additional axiom: • The (full) Partition-Associativity Axiom. Let $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ be a countably indexed family, and let $\{I_{j}\}_{j\in J}$ be a countable partition of $I$. Then $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ is summable if and only if $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I_{j}}$ is summable for every $j\in J$, and $\{\sum_{i\in I_{j}}x_{i}\}_{j\in J}$ is summable, in which case $\sum_{i\in I}x_{i}=\sum_{j\in J}\left(\sum_{i\in I_{j}}x_{i}\right)$ Note that this is a special case of the weak partition-associativity axiom, with a two-way, instead of a one-way, implication. A $\Sigma$-monoid is called a Partially Additive Monoid (PAM) when it satisfies the following additional axiom: • The Limit Axiom. Given $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$, a countably indexed family where$\{x_{i}\}_{i\in F}$ is summable for every finite $F\subseteq I$, then $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ is summable.
Definition 3.1. PCM-categories We define a PCM-category to be a locally small2i.e. we allow for a proper class of objects, but require that all homsets are indeed sets. category ${\mathcal{C}}$, together with, for all $X,Y\in Ob({\mathcal{C}})$, a partial function $\Sigma^{(X,Y)}$ from countably indexed families over ${\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ to ${\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ (we will often omit the superscript, when this is clear from the context). This class of partial functions is required to satisfy the following axioms: 1. (PCM-structure on hom-sets) $\left({\mathcal{C}}(X,Y),\Sigma^{(X,Y)}\right)$ is a PCM, for all $X,Y\in Ob({\mathcal{C}})$. 2. (Strong distributivity) Given summable families $\{f_{i}\in{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)\}_{i\in I}$ and $\{g_{j}\in{\mathcal{C}}(Y,Z)\}_{j\in J}$, then $\{g_{j}f_{i}\in{\mathcal{C}}(X,Z)\}_{(j,i)\in J\times I}$ is a summable family satisfying $\sum_{(j,i)\in J\times I}^{\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (X,Z)}g_{j}f_{i}\ =\ \left(\sum_{% j\in J}^{\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ (Y,Z)}g_{j}\right)\left(\sum_{i\in I}^{\ \ \ \ \ \ % \ \ \ (X,Y)}f_{i}\right)$
Definition 6.1. Let ${\mathcal{D}}$ be an arbitrary category, and let ${{\mathcal{C}}}$ be a PCM-category. For all $X\in Ob({{\mathcal{C}}})$ we define the functor $\gamma_{X,{\mathcal{D}}}:{\mathcal{D}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]$ by • (On objects) $\gamma_{X,{\mathcal{D}}}(U)=(X,U)$, for all $U\in Ob({\mathcal{D}})$, • (On arrows) Given $h\in{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)$, then $\gamma_{X,{\mathcal{D}}}(h)\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(X,V))$ is defined by $\gamma_{X,{\mathcal{D}}}(h)(a)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{lr}1_{X}&a=h\\ 0_{X}&\mbox{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$
Definition A.7. Let $X$ be an arbitrary Banach space. A series $\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}x_{i}$ is said to converge absolutely when $\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}\|x_{i}\|<\infty$. Alternatively, is is said to converge unconditionally when the series $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}x_{\sigma(j)}$ converges for arbitrary permutations $\sigma:{\mathbb{N}}\rightarrow{\mathbb{N}}$. (Unconditional summability can simply be thought of as permutation-independent convergence, in a more general setting.) It is standard that for any unconditionally convergent series, all rearrangements have the same sum; also, every subseries of an unconditionally convergent series is itself unconditionally convergent [Thorpe 1968].
Definition 4.1. Locally countable categories We say that a category ${\mathcal{D}}$ is locally countable when, for all $U,V\in Ob({{\mathcal{D}}})$, the homset ${\mathcal{D}}(U,V)$ is a countable set. We denote the full subcategory of Cat, whose objects are locally countable categories, by cCat.
Definition 1.1. Monoid semirings Let $(M,\cdot)$ be a monoid, and $(R,\times,+,1_{R},0_{R})$ be a unital semiring. The monoid semiring $R[M]$ is the unital semiring whose elements are functions $\eta:M\rightarrow R$ such that $\|\{m:\eta(m)\neq 0\}_{m\in M}\|<\infty$. The multiplication and addition in this semiring are given by • $(\eta\times\mu)(m)=\sum_{m=qp}\eta(q)\mu(p)$, • $(\eta+\mu)(m)=\eta(m)+\mu(m)$. The additive identity is the function $0(m)=0_{R}\ \forall m\in M$, and the multiplicative identity is the function $1(m)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{lr}1_{R}&m=1_{M}\\ 0_{R}&\mbox{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$ When $(M,\cdot)$ is a group, $R[M]$ is called the group semiring; similarly, when $R$ is a ring, then $R[M]$ is called the monoid (or group) ring.
Definition 7.1. Given a PCM-Category ${\mathcal{C}}$, and a locally small category ${\mathcal{D}}$, we define the functor 4Note that this is simply a functor, rather than a PCM-functor, since the product category ${\mathcal{C}}\times{\mathcal{D}}$ is not a PCM-category. However, the construction relies on the assumption that ${\mathcal{C}}$ is indeed a PCM-category. $(\underline{\ \ }\star\underline{\ \ }):{\mathcal{C}}\times{\mathcal{D}}% \rightarrow{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]$ as follows: • (Objects) Given $X\in Ob({\mathcal{C}})$ and $U\in Ob({\mathcal{D}})$, then $X\star U=(X,U)\in Ob({\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}])$ • (Arrows) Given $f\in{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ and $g\in{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)$, then $f\star g\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(Y,V))$ is the function $(f\star g)(h)\ =\ \left\{\begin{array}[]{lr}f&g=h\\ 0_{X,Y}&\mbox{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$ It is immediate that the family $\left\{(f\star g)(h)\right\}_{h\in{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)}$ is summable, and hence this is indeed an arrow of ${\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]$.
Definition 2.1. Partial Commutative Monoids (PCMs) Given sets $M$ and $I$, an $I$-indexed family of elements of $M$ is defined to be a function $x:I\rightarrow M$. For simplicity, we denote this by $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$. Throughout this paper, we restrict ourselves to countable (i.e. either finite or denumerably infinite) indexing sets, and hence countably indexed families. A partial commutative monoid or PCM is a non-empty set $M$ together with a partial function $\Sigma$ from indexed families of $M$ to elements of $M$. An indexed family of elements of $M$ is called summable when it is in the domain of $\Sigma$, and summation is required to satisfy the following two axioms: 1. The Unary Sum axiom Any family $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$, where $I=\{i^{\prime}\}$ is a singleton set, is summable, and $\sum_{i\in I}x_{i}=x_{i^{\prime}}$. 2. The Weak Partition-Associativity axiom Let $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ be a summable family, and let $\{I_{j}\}_{j\in J}$ be a countable partition1Following [Manes, Arbib 1986], we also allow countably many $I_{j}$ to be empty. of $I$. Then $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I_{j}}$ is summable for every $j\in J$, as is $\{\sum_{i\in I_{j}}x_{i}\}_{j\in J}$, and $\sum_{i\in I}x_{i}=\sum_{j\in J}\left(\sum_{i\in I_{j}}x_{i}\right)$ Given a summable family $x=\{x_{i}\}_{i\in I}$, we may write $\Sigma(x)$ (unambiguously) as $\sum_{i\in I}x_{i}$. In particular, if $I=\{1,\ldots,n\}$, we write $\Sigma(x)=x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots+x_{n}$, and if $I={\mathbb{N}}$, $\Sigma(x)=x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots$. Notice that by Weak Partition Associativity, we may equate different partitions of a summable family $x$, for example: $\displaystyle x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle x_{1}+(x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots+x_{n}+\cdots)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(x_{1}+x_{2})+(x_{3}+x_{4})+\cdots+(x_{n}+x_{n+1})+\cdots$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(x_{1}+x_{3}+x_{5}+\cdots)+(x_{2}+x_{4}+x_{6}+\cdots)$
Definition 2.5. PCM homomorphisms, the category of PCMs A homomorphism of PCMs is a function $f:(M,\Sigma)\rightarrow(N,\Sigma^{\prime})$ satisfying the following natural property: Given a summable family $\{m_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ of $(M,\Sigma)$, then $\{f(m_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ is a summable family of $(N,\Sigma^{\prime})$, and $f\left(\Sigma_{i\in I}m_{i}\right)\ =\ \Sigma^{\prime}_{i\in I}f(m_{i})$.
Definition 4.2. Given a PCM-category ${\mathcal{C}}\in Ob(\mbox{\bf Cat}_{\Sigma})$ and a locally countable category ${\mathcal{D}}\in Ob(\mbox{\bf cCat})$, we define their Cauchy product ${\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]\in Ob(\mbox{\bf Cat}_{\Sigma})$ as follows: • Objects $Ob({\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}])=Ob(\mathcal{C})\times Ob(\mathcal{D})$ • Arrows The homset ${\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(Y,V))$ consists of all functions $f:{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)\rightarrow{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ such that $\{f(a)\in{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)\}_{a\in{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)}$ is a summable family. • Composition Given $g\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((Y,V),(Z,W))$ and $f\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(Y,V))$ as functions $f:{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)\rightarrow{{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)\ \mbox{ and }\ g:{\mathcal% {D}}(V,W)\rightarrow{{\mathcal{C}}}(Y,Z)$ then $gf\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(Z,W))$ is the function from ${\mathcal{D}}(U,W)$ to ${{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Z)$ given by: $gf(c)=\sum_{\{(b,a):c=ba\}\subseteq{{\mathcal{D}}(V,W)\times{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)% }}g(b)f(a)$ For clarity, we will often use the shorthand notation $gf(c)=\sum_{c=ba}g(b)f(a)$ • Summation An indexed family $\{f_{i}\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(Y,V))\}_{i\in I}$ is summable exactly when $\{f_{i}(h)\in{{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)\}_{(i,h)\in I\times{\mathcal{D}}(U,V)}\ % \mbox{ is summable in }{{\mathcal{C}}}$ in which case $\left(\sum_{i\in I}f_{i}\right)(h)\ \stackrel{{\scriptstyle def.}}{{=}}\ \sum_% {i\in I}f_{i}(h)\ \in\ {{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$
Definition A.12. Let $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}y_{j}$ be an infinite series, and $\sum_{i=0}^{\alpha}x_{i}$ be a finite or infinite series in some Banach space $X$. We say that $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}y_{j}$ is a 0-padding of $\sum_{i=0}^{\alpha}x_{i}$ when there exists some injection $\eta:\{0,\ldots\alpha\}\rightarrow{\mathbb{N}}$ such that for all $j\in{\mathbb{N}}$, $y_{j}=\left\{\begin{array}[]{lr}x(i)&j=\eta(i)\\ 0&\mbox{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$
Definition 5.3. Let ${\mathcal{D}}$ be an arbitrary category, and let ${{\mathcal{C}}}$ be a PCM-category. For all $U\in Ob({\mathcal{D}})$, we define $\eta_{{\mathcal{C}},U}:{{\mathcal{C}}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]$ by • (on objects) $\eta_{{\mathcal{C}},U}(X)=(X,U)$, for all $X\in Ob({{\mathcal{C}}})$. • (on arrows) Given $h\in{{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$, then $\eta_{{\mathcal{C}},U}(h)\in{\mathcal{C}}[{\mathcal{D}}]((X,U),(Y,U))$ is the function $\eta_{{\mathcal{C}},U}(h):{\mathcal{D}}(U,U)\rightarrow{{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$ given by $\left(\eta_{{\mathcal{C}},U}(h)\right)(a)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{lr}h&a=1_{U}% \\ 0_{XY}&a\neq 1_{U}\end{array}\right.$
Definition 3.8. PCM-functors, the category $\mbox{\bf Cat}_{\Sigma}$ Given PCM-categories ${\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{D}}$, we say that a functor $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$ is a PCM-functor when: • Given a summable family $\{f_{i}\in{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)\}_{i\in I}$, then $\{\Gamma(f_{i})\in{\mathcal{D}}(\Gamma(X),\Gamma(Y))\}$ is a summable family, and $\Gamma\left(\sum_{i\in I}f_{i}\right)=\sum_{i\in I}\Gamma(f_{i})$ We denote the category of all PCM-categories and PCM-functors by $\mbox{\bf Cat}_{\Sigma}$.
Definition A.3. Let $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}$ be a formal (i. e. not necessarily convergent) series of real numbers. The $n^{th}$ partial sum is defined by $A_{n}=\sum_{j=0}^{n}a_{j}$. When $lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}(A_{n})$ exists, then the infinite series is said to converge. Note that convergence is permutation-dependent. Let $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}$ and $\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}b_{k}$, be series satisfying $b_{k}=a_{\sigma(j)}$, for some permutation $\sigma:\mathbb{N}\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$. Then the convergence of $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}$ is not enough to guarantee the convergence of $\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}b_{k}$. A convergent series $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}$ is said to converge absolutely when it satisfies the additional property that the non-negative series $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}|a_{j}|$ is convergent. Alternatively, a convergent series $\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}$ is said to be permutation-independent when $\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}a_{\sigma(i)}$ converges for arbitrary permutations $\sigma:{\mathbb{N}}\rightarrow{\mathbb{N}}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a simplicial category. The homotopy coherent center $\mathcal{Z}(\mathbf{C})$ of $\mathbf{C}$ is defined as the homotopy limit $\mathcal{Z}(\mathbf{C})=\operatorname{holim}\Pi^{\bullet}\mathbf{C}=c\mathbf{S% }(\Delta^{\bullet},\Pi^{\bullet}\mathbf{C})=\operatorname{Tot}(\Pi^{\bullet}% \mathbf{C})$ of the cosimplicial space $\Pi^{\bullet}\mathbf{C}$.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a simplicial category. The simplicial center $\mathrm{Z}(\mathbf{C})$ of $\mathbf{C}$ is the equalizer (in the category of spaces) of the two maps $\prod_{x}\mathbf{C}(x,x)\longrightarrow\prod_{y,z}\operatorname{Map}(\mathbf{C% }(y,z),\mathbf{C}(y,z))$ that are given by sending a family $\Phi=(\Phi_{x})$ to the map $f\mapsto f\Phi_{y}$ and the map $f\mapsto\Phi_{z}f$, respectively, in the $(y,z)$ component.
Definition 4.1. The equivariant model structure or fine model structure on ${\cal Map}(\cal S)$ is the model category ${\cal Map}(\cal S)_{\text{eq}}$ in which the underlying category is ${\cal Map}(\cal S)$, and in which a map $X\to Y$ between objects of ${\cal Map}(\cal S)$ is a weak equivalence (fibration) if and only for each $A\in\cal S$ it gives a weak equivalence (fibration) $\hom(O_{A},X)\to\hom(O_{A},Y)$ in $\cal S$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\cal D$ be a (not necessarily small) simplicial category. A functor $\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut:\cal D\to\cal S$ is representable if there is an object $D\in\cal D$ such that $\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut$ is naturally equivalent to $R^{D}$, where $R^{D}(D^{\prime})=\hom_{\cal D}(D,D^{\prime})$. A functor $\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut\colon\mathcal{C}% \rightarrow\cal S$ is called small if $\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut$ is a small weighted colimit of representables.
Definition 3.6. The category of maps in $\cal S^{\cal D}$, denoted ${\cal Map}(\cal S^{\cal D})$, is the category whose objects are the arrows $f\colon\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut\to\smash{% \underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{Y}}}{Y}}\mathstrut$ in $\cal S^{\cal D}$. A morphism $f\to f^{\prime}$ is a commutative diagram $\xymatrix{\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut\ar[d]^{f}% \ar[r]&\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut^{\prime}\ar[d]% ^{f^{\prime}}\\ \smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{Y}}}{Y}}\mathstrut\ar[r]&\smash{% \underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{Y}}}{Y}}\mathstrut^{\prime}}$
Definition 3.3. A collection $\cal L$ of objects in a category $\mathcal{B}$ is said to be locally small in $\mathcal{B}$ if for every object $X$ of $\mathcal{B}$ there exists a set of objects $\cal O_{X}\subset\cal L$ such that any map $Y\to X$ with $Y\in\cal L$ can be factored as a composite $Y\to Y^{\prime}\to X$ for some $Y^{\prime}\in\cal O_{X}$.
Definition 2.15. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a monoidal category, $\mathcal{M}$ a right $\mathcal{C}$-module and $\mathcal{N}$ a left $\mathcal{C}$-module. A balanced $\mathcal{C}$-module functor is a functor $F:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{N}\to\mathcal{D}$ equipped with an isomorphism $F\circ(\odot\times\operatorname{Id}_{\mathcal{N}})\simeq F\circ(\operatorname{% Id}_{\mathcal{M}}\times\odot):\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{N}\to% \mathcal{D}$ satisfying the following conditions: • $F$ preserves finite colimits separately in each variable. • For $a,b\in\mathcal{C}$, $x\in\mathcal{M}$, $y\in\mathcal{N}$, the evident diagrams $\xymatrix{&F(x,y)\ar[ld]_{\simeq}\ar[rd]^{\simeq}\\ F(x\odot\mathbf{1},y)\ar[rr]^{\simeq}&&F(x,\mathbf{1}\odot y)\\ }$ $\xymatrix{F((x\odot a)\odot b,y)\ar[r]^{\simeq}\ar[d]^{\simeq}&F(x\odot a,b% \odot y)\ar[r]^{\simeq}&F(x,a\odot(b\odot y))\ar[d]^{\simeq}\\ F(x\odot(a\otimes b),y)\ar[rr]^{\simeq}&&F(x,(a\otimes b)\odot y)\\ }$ are commutative. We use $\operatorname{Fun}^{bal}_{\mathcal{C}}(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{N};\mathcal{D})$ to denote the category of balanced $\mathcal{C}$-module functors $F:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{N}\to\mathcal{D}$. The tensor product of $\mathcal{M}$ and $\mathcal{N}$ over $\mathcal{C}$ is a category $\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{N}$, which admits all finite colimits, together with a balanced $\mathcal{C}$-module functor $\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{N}\to\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{% \mathcal{C}}\mathcal{N}$, such that, for every category $\mathcal{D}$, which admits all finite colimits, composition with $\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}$ induces an equivalence $\operatorname{Fun}(\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{N},\mathcal{D})% \simeq\operatorname{Fun}^{bal}_{\mathcal{C}}(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{N};\mathcal{% D})$.
Definition 3.22. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be two monoidal categories and $\mathcal{M}$ a $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule. We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is invertible if there is a $\mathcal{D}$-$\mathcal{C}$-bimodule $\mathcal{N}$ and equivalences $\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}\mathcal{N}\simeq\mathcal{C}$ as $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{C}$-bimodules and $\mathcal{N}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{M}\simeq\mathcal{D}$ as $\mathcal{D}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodules. If such an invertible $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule exists, $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ are said to be Morita equivalent.
Definition 4.16. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) braided monoidal categories. (1) A monoidal left $\mathcal{C}$-module is a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) monoidal category $\mathcal{M}$ equipped with a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) braided monoidal functor $\phi_{\mathcal{M}}:\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{rev}}\to\mathfrak{Z}(\mathcal{M})$. (2) A monoidal right $\mathcal{D}$-module is a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) monoidal category $\mathcal{M}$ equipped with a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) braided monoidal functor $\phi_{\mathcal{M}}:\mathcal{D}\to\mathfrak{Z}(\mathcal{M})$. (3) A monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule is a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) monoidal category $\mathcal{M}$ equipped with a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) braided monoidal functor $\phi_{\mathcal{M}}:\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{rev}}\boxtimes\mathcal{D}\to\mathfrak{% Z}(\mathcal{M})$. A monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule is said to be closed if $\phi_{\mathcal{M}}$ is an equivalence.
Definition 3.7. A $\mathbf{k}$-linear monoidal category is indecomposable if it is neither zero nor the direct sum of two nonzero $\mathbf{k}$-linear monoidal categories.
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a monoidal category and $\mathcal{M}$ a left $\mathcal{C}$-module. Given objects $x,y\in\mathcal{M}$, we define an object $[x,y]\in\mathcal{C}$, if exists, by the mapping property $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(a,[x,y])\simeq\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{M}% }(a\odot x,y),$ and refer to it as the internal hom between $x$ and $y$. We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is enriched in $\mathcal{C}$, if $[x,y]$ exists for every pair of objects $x,y\in\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 3.15. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a $\mathbf{k}$-linear monoidal category with a tensor unit $\mathbf{1}$. A $\mathbf{k}$-linear left $\mathcal{C}$-module $\mathcal{M}$ is faithful if $e\odot\mathcal{M}\not\simeq 0$ for every nonzero subobject $e$ of $\mathbf{1}$.
Definition 3.4. A $\mathbf{k}$-linear monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ is a $\mathbf{k}$-linear category such that the tensor product $\otimes:\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ is a balanced $\mathbf{k}$-module functor.
Definition 4.8. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a braided monoidal category. The centralizer of $\mathcal{C}$, denoted by $\mathfrak{Z}_{2}(\mathcal{C})$, is the full subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ consisting of those objects $x$ that are symmetric to all objects, i.e. $\beta_{c,x}\circ\beta_{x,c}=\operatorname{Id}_{x\otimes c}$ for all $c\in\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 5.15. We say that a $\mathbf{k}$-linear category $\mathcal{C}$ is semisimple if $\mathcal{C}\simeq\operatorname{RMod}_{A}(\mathbf{k})$ for some finite-dimensional semisimple $k$-algebra $A$. A multi-fusion category over $k$ is a rigid semisimple $\mathbf{k}$-linear monoidal category. A fusion category over $k$ is a multi-fusion category over $k$ with a simple tensor unit.
Definition 3.19. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be monoidal categories and $\mathcal{M}$ a $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule. We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is right dualizable, if there exists a $\mathcal{D}$-$\mathcal{C}$-bimodule $\mathcal{N}$ equipped with bimodule functors $u:\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{N}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{M}$ and $v:\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}\mathcal{N}\to\mathcal{C}$ such that the composed bimodule functors $\mathcal{M}\simeq\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}\mathcal{D}\xrightarrow{% \operatorname{Id}_{\mathcal{M}}\boxtimes u}\mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}% \mathcal{N}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{M}\xrightarrow{v\boxtimes% \operatorname{Id}_{\mathcal{M}}}\mathcal{C}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{M}% \simeq\mathcal{M}$ $\mathcal{N}\simeq\mathcal{D}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}\mathcal{N}\xrightarrow{u% \boxtimes\operatorname{Id}_{\mathcal{N}}}\mathcal{N}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}% \mathcal{M}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}\mathcal{N}\xrightarrow{\operatorname{Id}_{% \mathcal{N}}\boxtimes v}\mathcal{N}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{C}\simeq% \mathcal{N}$ are isomorphic to the identity functor. In this case, we say that the $\mathcal{D}$-$\mathcal{C}$-bimodule $\mathcal{N}$ is left dualizable.
Definition 5.17. Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be braided monoidal categories and $\mathcal{M}$ a monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule. If, in addition, $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D},\mathcal{M}$ are multi-fusion categories, then $\mathcal{M}$ is called a multi-fusion $\mathcal{C}$-$\mathcal{D}$-bimodule.
Definition 4.9. A braided monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ is called closed (or nondegenerate) if $\mathfrak{Z}_{2}(\mathcal{C})=\mathbf{k}$. It is called exact if there is a monoidal category $\mathcal{D}$ such that $\mathcal{C}$ is braided monoidally equivalent to $\mathfrak{Z}(\mathcal{D})$, i.e. $\mathcal{C}\simeq^{br}\mathfrak{Z}(\mathcal{D})$.
Definition 3.5. Given a $\mathbf{k}$-linear monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$, a $\mathbf{k}$-linear left $\mathcal{C}$-module $\mathcal{M}$ is a $\mathbf{k}$-linear category such that the action $\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{M}$ is a balanced $\mathbf{k}$-module functor. The notions of a $\mathbf{k}$-linear right module and a $\mathbf{k}$-linear bimodule are defined similarly.
Definition 4.24 ([BD]). An r-category is a monoidal category $\mathcal{C}$ with a tensor unit $\mathbf{1}$ such that $\mathcal{C}$ is enriched in itself and that the functor $[-,\mathbf{1}]:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}}$ is an equivalence. In this case, we will denote the functor $[-,\mathbf{1}]$ by $\mathfrak{D}$.
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category. An algebra in the monoidal category $\operatorname{\mathcal{E}nd}(\mathcal{C})$ is called a monad over $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 4.20. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) braided monoidal category and $\mathcal{M},\mathcal{N}$ right monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-modules. A monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-module functor $F:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$ is a ($\mathbf{k}$-linear) monoidal functor equipped with an isomorphism of monoidal functors $F\circ f_{\mathcal{M}}\simeq f_{\mathcal{N}}:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{N}$ such that the evident diagram $\xymatrix{F(f_{\mathcal{M}}(a)\otimes x)\ar[r]^{\sim}\ar[d]_{\sim}&F(x\otimes f% _{\mathcal{M}}(a))\ar[d]^{\sim}\\ f_{\mathcal{N}}(a)\otimes F(x)\ar[r]^{\sim}&F(x)\otimes f_{\mathcal{N}}(a)\\ }$ is commutative for $a\in\mathcal{C}$ and $x\in\mathcal{M}$. Two right monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-modules are said to be equivalent if there is an invertible monoidal $\mathcal{C}$-module functor $F:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$.
